In .NET 10 (Android 15+), `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` is deprecated and no longer functions. The replacement is **edge-to-edge insets handling** via `WindowInsets`.

## Recommended approach

**1. Set `SoftInputMode` to `AdjustNothing` and handle insets yourself:**

In your `MainActivity.cs` or platform code:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

Window.SetSoftInputMode(SoftInputMode.AdjustNothing);

ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
```

```csharp
class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        // imeInsets.Bottom gives keyboard height in pixels
        view.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, imeInsets.Bottom);
        return insets;
    }
}
```

**2. Or use the simpler MAUI-level workaround — keep `AdjustResize` but opt out of edge-to-edge:**

In `MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);
    // Disable the new edge-to-edge enforcement
    AndroidX.Activity.EdgeToEdge.Disable(this);
}
```

This restores the .NET 9 behavior where `AdjustResize` works again.

## Summary

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| Insets listener | Future-proof, works with edge-to-edge | More code |
| `EdgeToEdge.Disable()` | One-liner, restores old behavior | May break on future Android versions |

For a chat screen, the insets approach (option 1) is preferred — it gives you precise control over the bottom padding so your input bar slides up smoothly with the keyboard.
